SDSS Classification¶

This notebook will perform the exploratory data analysis required on the data sets found within the ./data/stellar_classification.csv file. This file contains data from the Sloan Digital Sky Survey. We will be using the features within this data set to predict each record is a GALAXY, QSO ("Quasi-Stellar Object), or a STAR.

This data set is imbalanced, so we should eventually be using some kind of data balancing algorithm (e.g. SMOTE)

EDA + Feature Engineering¶

Data description taken from the Kaggle page (https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/fedesoriano/stellar-classification-dataset-sdss17):

The data consists of 100,000 observations of space taken by the SDSS (Sloan Digital Sky Survey). Every observation is described by 17 feature columns and 1 class column which identifies it to be either a star, galaxy or quasar.

  1. obj_ID = Object Identifier, the unique value that identifies the object in the image catalog used by the CAS
  2. alpha = Right Ascension angle (at J2000 epoch)
  3. delta = Declination angle (at J2000 epoch)
  4. u = Ultraviolet filter in the photometric system
  5. g = Green filter in the photometric system
  6. r = Red filter in the photometric system
  7. i = Near Infrared filter in the photometric system
  8. z = Infrared filter in the photometric system
  9. run_ID = Run Number used to identify the specific scan
  10. rereun_ID = Rerun Number to specify how the image was processed
  11. cam_col = Camera column to identify the scanline within the run
  12. field_ID = Field number to identify each field
  13. spec_obj_ID = Unique ID used for optical spectroscopic objects (this means that 2 different observations with the same spec_obj_ID must share the output class)
  14. class = object class (galaxy, star or quasar object)
  15. redshift = redshift value based on the increase in wavelength
  16. plate = plate ID, identifies each plate in SDSS
  17. MJD = Modified Julian Date, used to indicate when a given piece of SDSS data was taken
  18. fiber_ID = fiber ID that identifies the fiber that pointed the light at the focal plane in each observation

I can easily throw away obj_ID, alpha, delta, run_ID, rerun_ID, cam_col, field_ID, spec_obj_id, plate, MJD, fiber_ID

A lot of these columns are identifies for the SDSS system. alpha and delta describe positional information in relation to the night sky. I don't anticipate position being indicative of object class.

However, redshift is also an measure of position. "Redshift" is a measure of how far away an object is from us, the observer. There might be some correlation between far away objects being a GALAXY, STAR, or QSO, so I'll leave it in for now.

So the features used:

u g r i z and redshift

labels:

class

def plot_corr(df):
    fig = go.Figure()

    fig.add_trace(
        go.Heatmap(
            x=df.columns,
            y=df.index,
            z=df.values,
            xgap=1,
            ygap=1,
            zmin=-1,
            zmax=1
            
            
        )
    )

    fig.update_layout(
        template="plotly_dark",
        height=800,
        title={
            'text':'Correlation Matrix',
            'x' : 0.5
        }
    )
    return fig

fig = plot_corr(corr_df)
plotly.offline.iplot(fig)

Interestingly, there is some pretty high correlation between a few of the features. Namely g, u, and z are all highly correlated with eachother, while r and i are also highly correlated as well. However, considering they are all uniquely different measures of photometry we should leave them in. Each of these variables describe a corresponding intensity in specific wavebands of light.

# rows of 3

def plot_distributions(df):
    
    fig = make_subplots(rows = 2, cols = 3, vertical_spacing=0.3)
    for idx, col in enumerate(df.columns):
        irow = int(idx/3)+1
        icol = idx%3+1
        trace = go.Histogram(
            x=df[col], 
            name=col
        )
        fig.add_trace(trace, row=irow, col=icol)
        fig.update_xaxes(title_text=col, row=irow, col=icol)
        fig.update_yaxes(title_text="Count")

    fig.update_layout(
        template='plotly_dark',
        height=700
    )
    
    return fig

Scaling¶

The above distributions are multimodal, and therefore not perfectly normal. It would probably help our classification algorithms if we were to normalize and scale each variable.

Additionally, redshift is a very skewed distribution, that represents the expansion of space from the light received from that object. (Think: redshift $\propto$ distance). In the below equation, let $z$ = redshift.

$$ z = \frac{\lambda_{obs}}{\lambda_{rest}} - 1 $$

From this equation, we can infer that adding a bias of $1$ to all redshifts $z$ would result in the loss of any information. In order to adequately scale our redshift distribution, we will be applying a bias of $1$ and then a subsequent $log$ transformation.

In [10]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, PowerTransformer

# transform redshift first
redshift_train = X_train['redshift'].copy()
redshift_train = redshift_train.to_numpy().reshape(-1,1)
redshift_test = X_test['redshift'].copy()
redshift_test = redshift_test.to_numpy().reshape(-1,1)

# there are negative values, so we want to bias
bias = 1
redshift_train = redshift_train + bias
redshift_test = redshift_test + bias



# Power Transformer
PT = PowerTransformer(method='yeo-johnson')
PT.fit(redshift_train)
redshift_train = PT.transform(redshift_train)
redshift_test = PT.transform(redshift_test)
X_train['redshift_biased_transformed'] = redshift_train
X_test['redshift_biased_transformed'] = redshift_test

X_train.drop("redshift", axis=1, inplace=True)
X_test.drop("redshift", axis=1, inplace=True)

# updated features list
features.remove("redshift")
features.append("redshift_biased_transformed")

# log transform
# redshift = np.log(redshift)
# X_train['redshift_bias_transformed'] = redshift

fig = plot_distributions(X_train)
fig.show()

def plot_pie(data, title_str):

    fig = px.pie(data, names="class")
    
    fig.update_layout(
        template="plotly_dark",
        title={
                "text":title_str,
                "x":0.5
            }
    )

    return fig
In [14]:
fig = plot_pie(Y_train, "Proportion of Classifications - PreSMOTE" )
fig.show()

From the above distribution, we can see there is a class imbalance. GALAXY makes up ~60% of the labels, leaving ~40% to both the STAR and QSO labels. We should balance these labels using SMOTE and see if our performance increases.
